<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="409" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1196,1221]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to 
<collectingRegion box="[672,796,1196,1221]" country="Guatemala" name="Guatemala" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">
<collectingCountry box="[672,796,1196,1221]" name="Guatemala" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, the country with the only locality where the species has been recorded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="409" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1268,1293]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Distribution.</emphasis>
Only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[613,661,1269,1293]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Guatemalan part of 
<collectingRegion box="[1060,1150,1268,1293]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
province. Its distribution may be related to tropical montane rain forests, most of which have been transformed to coffee plantations (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="409" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1375,1400]" pageId="8" pageNumber="409">Remarks.</emphasis>
In some females, the notch on anterior margin of clypeus is underdeveloped and with deeper punctures on sides of supraclypeal elevation. Pubescence of metanotum may be mixed with short dark hairs.
</paragraph>
